'''''Benefits Street''''' is a British documentary series broadcast on [[Channel 4]]. It was first aired on 6 January 2014, and ran for five episodes. The show was filmed by documenting the lives of several residents of James Turner Street, [[Winson Green]], [[Birmingham]], England, where newspapers including the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that 90% of the residents claim [[Welfare state in the United Kingdom|benefits]]. It shows benefits claimants committing crimes, including a demonstration of how to [[shoplifting|shoplift]], and portrays a situation in which people are dependent on welfare payments and lack the motivation to seek employment.

The show was controversial, with the police, Channel 4 and the media regulator [[Ofcom]] receiving hundreds of complaints. There were [[Twitter]] death threats made against the residents of the street. Channel 4 was accused of making [[poverty porn]]. Many of those taking part claimed that they were misled by the documentary makers. However, the producers of ''Benefits Street'' defended the series, arguing that the reaction to it demonstrated the importance of making such a documentary. The series was mentioned in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], and prompted some political debate on the topic of welfare. ''Benefits Street'' gave Channel 4 their highest viewing figures for any show since 2012.

==Background==
In 2012, Love Productions approached the BBC with the idea for a programme that would feature a prominent member of the business community working with unemployed people, but the show did not come to fruition after the unnamed individual had to withdraw from it because of other commitments. The format for the series that would later become ''Benefits Street'' was then suggested, but the BBC declined to commission the series because it was producing a number of other programmes concerning similar issues, such as ''[[People Like Us (Harpurhey)|People Like Us]]'' and ''Nick and Margaret: We All Pay Your Benefits''. Love Productions then suggested the format to Channel 4, which agreed to commission the programme.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jamie |last=Doward |first2=Tara |last2=Conlan |url=http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/jan/18/bbc-rejected-benefits-street-two-years-ago |title=BBC rejected early version of Benefits Street two years ago |newspaper=The Observer |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=18 January 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref>

Writing in ''[[The Observer]]'' in January 2014, Nick Mirsky, head of documentaries at Channel 4, said that Love Productions intentionally selected an area where a high proportion of the residents were in receipt of welfare payments "to show the effect of benefit cuts on a community for whom they were the principal source of income".<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-10>{{cite news|url=http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jan/10/benefits-street-documentary-reality |title=Benefits Street struck a nerve <U+2013> exposing how vital a documentary it is |first=Nick |last=Mirsky |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> The filming and production process took eighteen months.<ref name=Independent-2014-01-07>{{cite news|first=Ian |last=Burrell |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/tv-radio/channel-4s-benefits-street-sparks-anger-and-threats-of-violence-9044880.html |title=<U+2018>Benefits Street<U+2019>: Channel 4 documentary sparks anger and threats of violence |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=7 January 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> Both Mirsky, and Ralph Lee, Channel 4's head of factual programming, said the residents of James Turner Street were consulted about the series before filming began.<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-10/><ref name=Independent-2014-01-10>{{cite news|first=Daisy |last=Wyatt |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/benefits-street-channel-4-boss-denies-shows-residents-were-duped-9051050.html |title=Benefits Street: Channel 4 boss denies show's residents were duped |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref> Cameras observed them over the course of a twelve month period.<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-10/> The decision to call the series ''Benefits Street'' was taken two weeks before the programme aired.<ref name=Independent-2014-01-10/> The comedian [[Frank Skinner]], who is from the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], was approached to narrate the documentary but turned it down because he had concerns about how people from Birmingham would be portrayed, and did not wish to criticise the city.<ref>{{cite news|first=Roz |last=Laws |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/frank-skinner-turned-down-benefits-6503474 |title=Frank Skinner turned down Benefits Street job over fears about how Brummies would be portrayed |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=13 January 2014 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> The [[voice-over]] was provided by former ''[[Coronation Street]]'' actor [[Tony Hirst]] instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hobsons-international.com/voices/1754/tony_hirst |title=Tony Hirst - voiceover artists |publisher=Hobsons International |date= |accessdate=13 February 2014 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6NMCE79Se |archivedate=13 February 2014 |quote=[Hirst] can be heard on Absolute Radio, the long running Discovery series, 'How it's Made' and is the voice of Channel 4's 'Benefit Street'}}</ref>

The first episode of ''Benefits Street'' was aired at 9:00 pm on Monday 6 January 2014,<ref>{{cite news|first=Hatty |last=Collier |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/07/tvratings-channel4 |title=Channel 4's Benefits Street claims 4.3 million viewers |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=7 January 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> and ran for five episodes.<ref name=Independent-2014-01-07/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1199105/benefits-street-white-dee-invites-nick-clegg |title=Benefits Street: White Dee Invites Nick Clegg |publisher=British Sky Broadcasting |work=Sky News |date=22 January 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> A live one-hour debate to discuss issues raised by the series was then scheduled to air after the final episode, Channel 4 announcing plans for this a few days after the second episode had been transmitted.<ref name=C4-2014-06-16/> During the week following the broadcasting of the third episode, [[West Midlands Police]] charged several James Turner Street residents with drugs related offences in connection with a raid their officers had carried out in June 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-25894192 |work=BBC News |title=Benefits Street: Seven charged with drug offences |publisher=BBC |date=25 January 2014 |accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Adam |last=Withnall |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/benefits-street-residents-charged-with-drug-offences-9085986.html |title=Benefits Street residents charged with drug offences |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=26 January 2014 |accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> Those facing charges included some people seen in episodes of the series.<ref name=Mail-2014-01-27/> Channel 4 said they had no plans to alter any footage from the episodes yet to be transmitted.<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Hall |first2=Chris |last2=Hastings |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2546066/Millionaire-Tory-pockets-thousands-pounds-month-renting-damp-home-hard-families-Benefits-Street.html?ITO=1490&ns_mchannel=rss&ns_campaign=1490 |title=Tory Paul Nischal 'pockets thousands' by renting out Benefits Street house |newspaper=Daily Mail |publisher=Daily Mail and General Trust |date=26 January 2014 |accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>

On 23 January, the ''[[Birmingham Mail]]'' reported that some ''Benefits Street'' branded merchandise, such as [[mug]]s and [[T-shirt]]s were being produced for sale over the internet by individuals wishing to cash in on the programme.<ref name=Birmingham-Mail-2014-01-23>{{cite news|first=Paul |last=Suart |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/ebay-sellers-cashing-benefits-street-6552789 |title=Ebay sellers cashing in on Benefits Street |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=23 January 2014 |accessdate=28 January 2014}}</ref> As the series came to a close on 10 February, Love Productions confirmed to the ''Birmingham Mail'' that it was investigating potential locations for a second series, but that this would not be filmed in Birmingham.<ref>{{cite news|first=Paul |last=Suart |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/benefits-street-makers-planning-second-6692944 |title=Benefits Street makers planning second series |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref> Channel 5 confirmed to ''[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]'' magazine that it was in the process of filming a similar documentary, provisionally titled ''Living on the Social'', in which individuals and families would discuss their lives on welfare.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a550538/channel-5-developing-benefits-street-style-series.html |title=Channel 5 developing Benefits Street-style series - TV News |publisher=Digital Spy |date=12 February 2014 |accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Greenwood |first=Carl |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/benefits-street-channel-5-announces-3136602 |title=Benefits Street: Channel 5 announces it is developing own Benefits Street style series called Living on the Social |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Daily Mirror |date=12 February 2014 |accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref> Love Productions also announced plans for ''[[Famous, Rich and Hungry]]'', a two-part documentary for the BBC's ''[[Sport Relief]]'' that would see celebrities spending time with families experiencing [[food poverty]] in order to explore the issue.<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Plunkett |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/14/benefits-street-sports-relief-food-poverty-love-productions |title=Benefits Street producer makes BBC Sports Relief series on food poverty |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 February 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>

[[File:James Turner Street - geograph.org.uk - 987113.jpg|thumb|right|James Turner Street, seen here in 2008, is the setting for ''Benefits Street'']]
===James Turner Street===
James Turner Street is a residential street of [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] [[terraced house]]s in the Winson Green area of Birmingham.<ref name=Chinn>{{cite news|first=Carl |last=Chinn |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/lifestyle/nostalgia/carl-chinn-benefits-street-history-6496189 |title=Carl Chinn on Benefits Street history |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=Mirror-2014-01-22>{{cite news|last=Fricker |first=Martin |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/benefits-street-james-turner-street-3051297 |title=Benefits Street: James Turner Street in Birmingham was named after hard-working teacher |newspaper=Daily Mirror |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=22 January 2014 |accessdate=28 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=BBC-2014-02-10>{{cite web|last=Cavallaro |first=Cassandra |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-25848423 |work=BBC News |title=Benefits Street: 'Living the dream' 100 years ago |publisher=BBC |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref> The street is in the city's [[Soho, West Midlands|Soho]] Ward, part of the [[Birmingham Ladywood (UK Parliament constituency)|Ladywood constituency]], and has a [[B postcode area#B18|B18 postcode]].<ref name="MLI">{{cite web|url=https://localview.birmingham.gov.uk/My_Local_Information/Sites/MyLocalInformation/|title=My Local Information/|publisher=Birmingham City Council|accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>

It is first recorded in local records as Osborne Street in 1877,<ref name="Tyler">{{cite web|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/benefits-street-man-behind-tvs-6535817|title=Benefits Street: The man behind TV's most notorious street|last=Tyler|first=Jane|date=22 January 2014|work=Birmingham Mail|publisher=Trinity Mirror|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=Express-2014-01-23>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/455471/BENEFITS-STREET-The-real-James-Turner-a-respected-teacher-would-turn-in-his-grave |title=Benefits Street: The real James Turner <U+2013> a respected teacher <U+2013> would 'turn in his grave' |newspaper=Daily Express |publisher=Northern and Shell |date=23 January 2014 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> and given its present name in 1882.<ref name="Tyler" /> According to education historian Alison Wheatley, the street is possibly named after a James Turner who taught at [[King Edward's School, Birmingham|King Edward's School]] in Birmingham, and the name may have been suggested by a former pupil, who became a [[Urban planner|town planner]], as a way of honouring Turner's legacy.<ref name=Mirror-2014-01-22/><ref name="Tyler" /><ref name=Express-2014-01-23/> However, the Birmingham historian [[Carl Chinn]] believes the street was named for a local businessman and partner in the firm Hammond, Turner & Sons, a manufacturer of buttons.<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-29>{{cite news|first=Jon |last=Henley |url=http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/jan/29/benefits-street-a-spiral-of-decline |title=Benefits Street: the hard-working history that Channel 4 left out |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=29 January 2014 |accessdate=29 January 2014}}</ref> 

Of Winson Green, Chinn writes that it was originally developed as a "better-off working class district", but that by the latter part of the 20th century, many of the properties in the area were falling into decay.<ref name=Chinn/> Dr Chris Upton, [[Reader (academic rank)|reader]] in public history at the city's [[Newman University, Birmingham|Newman University]] has described the street as part of a "ribbon development" of suburban districts built as Birmingham expanded during the latter part of the 19th century.<ref name=BBC-2014-02-10/> While many of the street's original residents were locals who moved from the inner city [[back-to-back houses]], some had moved from as far away as [[London]] and [[Cornwall]] to work in Birmingham.<ref name=BBC-2014-02-10/><ref name=Post-2014-02-06/> Upton describes them as "the respectable working class"{{mdash}}skilled workers who earned around 30 [[Shilling (British coin)|shilling]]s (<U+00A3>1.50) per week, and who in many cases could even afford to employ a [[maid]].<ref name=BBC-2014-02-10/> Those who grew prosperous moved to wealthier areas, and were replaced by immigrants from Asia and the [[West Indies]], who came to the UK during the years after [[World War II]].<ref name=Post-2014-02-06/> A high proportion of those who lived in the area were employed by [[Economy of Birmingham|Birmingham's industrial economy]], which enjoyed prosperity until the collapse of the city's manufacturing industry during the early 1980s, resulting in mass unemployment.<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-29/> Professor Steven McCabe of [[Birmingham City Business School]] has noted that Birmingham lost 200,000 manufacturing jobs between 1971 and 1981, and that the city's [[Gross domestic product|GDP per capita]], which in 1976 was the highest for a UK city outside the [[South East England|south east region]], had fallen to become the lowest in England seven years later.<ref name=Post-2014-02-06>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/business/business-opinion/steven-mccabe-benefits-street---6679915 |first=Steven |last=McCabe |title=Benefits Street - and a warning from history |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Post |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref>

During the 1980s, unemployment in Birmingham reached 20%, and McCabe says that in many areas, including James Turner Street, this figure has not reduced since that decade.<ref name=Post-2014-02-06/> [[Clare Short]], who grew up in the area and represented Winson Green as [[Member of Parliament]] for Ladywood for 27 years, has said that along with high unemployment came a "new culture of drugs, crime and mental health problems."<ref name=Guardian-2014-02-04/> On their website, Channel 4 have described James Turner Street as "one of Britain's most benefits-dependent streets".<ref name=Birmingham-Mail-2014-01-06>{{cite news|first=Paul |last=Suart |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/benefits-street-tv-show-lied-6470342 |title=Benefits Street TV show lied to us, say Winson Green residents |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=6 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> Sources such as the ''Daily Mail'' and ''The Guardian'' reported in January 2014 that 90% of the street's residents are benefits claimants.<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-29/><ref name=Mail-2014-01-07>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2535138/Star-controversial-Channel-4-series-Benefits-Street-police-bail-following-drugs-raid-home.html|title=Backlash over TV lessons in how to shoplift: Flood of complaints triggers police probe into Channel 4 documentary|last=Wright|first=Stephen|last2=Dolan|first2= Andy |first3=Francesca |last3=Infante|date=7 January 2014|work=Daily Mail|publisher=Daily Mail and General Trust|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref>

==Synopsis==
Narrated by [[Tony Hirst]], the series is presented in a [[fly on the wall]] documentary format that follows a year in the lives of the residents of James Turner Street, a road in the Winson Green area of Birmingham which Channel 4 describes as "one of Britain's most benefit-dependent streets". The programme portrays a situation in which people are dependent on welfare payments, and often lack the motivation to find employment. Some residents are seen committing crimes such as shoplifting, and attempting to raise money to support themselves and their families. Others are shown to have more ambition, such as a young mother who wants to become a model. The series also aims to show the street's sense of community spirit, with residents helping each other in times of difficulty.

