==Reception==

===Political and media response===
The programme led to some political debate on the issue of welfare. Speaking in the House of Commons on 13 January, [[Iain Duncan Smith]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]] suggested the programme justified the changes being made by the [[Cameron ministry|Conservative<U+2013>Liberal Democrat coalition government]]'s [[Welfare Reform Act 2012|Welfare Reform Act]].<ref name=Mirror-2014-01-13/> The following week, Duncan Smith gave a speech to mark the tenth anniversary of his [[Centre for Social Justice]] in which he said that areas of the country were being ghettoised by long term unemployment and had remained largely hidden from the rest of society.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dominiczak |first=Peter |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/10590933/Iain-Duncan-Smith-Ill-stop-Benefits-Street-Britain.html |title=Iain Duncan Smith: I<U+2019>ll stop Benefits Street Britain |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=22 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=Guardian-2014-01-22>{{cite news|first=Patrick |last=Wintour |url=http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jan/22/duncan-smith-benefits-street-shock |title=Benefits Street reveals 'ghetto' reality, says Iain Duncan Smith |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=22 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25866259 |work=BBC News |title=Benefits Street reaction shows poor 'ghettoised', says Duncan Smith |publisher=BBC |date=23 January 2014 |accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> Conservative MP [[Simon Hart]] raised the subject of ''Benefits Street'' at [[Prime Minister's Questions]] on 15 January, saying that a street of the type seen in the series existed "in every constituency in the land".<ref name=BBC-2014-01-15>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-25746824 |work=BBC News |title=PMQs: Benefit Street 'in every constituency' says MP |publisher=BBC |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.westerntelegraph.co.uk/news/10949470.MP_stands_by_his___39_Benefits_Street__39__in_every_constituency__comments/ |title=MP stands by his 'Benefits Street' in every constituency comments |newspaper=Western Telegraph |publisher= |date=20 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> Prime Minister and Conservative leader [[David Cameron]] responded that the government should "intervene in people's lives" to get them off benefits and into employment.<ref name=BBC-2014-01-15/> After declining an invitation to visit James Turner Street, Deputy Prime Minister [[Nick Clegg]], leader of the [[Liberal Democrats]] said that he believed both left and right arguments on welfare were wrong. "We want a welfare system which is compassionate."<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-22/> Shortly after Clegg's comments, Birmingham councillor Desmond Jaddoo told the ''Birmingham Mail'' that he had compiled letters to Clegg, Cameron and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] leader [[Ed Miliband]] on behalf of some James Turner Street residents inviting them to visit the street and asking for help to find employment.<ref name=Birmingham-Mail-2014-01-23/>

Writing for the ''[[Gazette and Herald|Wiltshire Gazette and Herald]]'', the Liberal Democrat MP [[Duncan Hames]] argued the programme would contribute little to the subject: "We do need to have a rational, informed debate about how to improve our welfare system, but the editorial line taken by supposedly factual <U+2018>reality TV<U+2019> adds very little to that."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/10957620.Duncan_Hames__MP_for_Chippenham______Reality_TV____does_nothing_for_those_wanting_to_work/?ref=var_0 |title=Duncan Hames, MP for Chippenham <U+2013> <U+2018>Reality TV<U+2019> does nothing for those wanting to work |newspaper=The Wiltshire Gazette and Herald |publisher=Newsquest |date=23 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> The programme was condemned by the current Ladywood MP, Labour's [[Shabana Mahmood]]: "I found it shocking that Channel 4 or any other organisation would present poverty as entertainment. It was profoundly wrong."<ref>{{cite news|first=Jonathan |last=Walker |url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/news/local-news/channel-4-show-benefits-street-6482174 |title=Channel 4 show Benefits Street exploits the poor, says Birmingham MP |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Post |date=9 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> In the ''[[Radio Times]]'', [[Clare Short]], who represented the constituency prior to Mahmood, said the series was "totally unrepresentative" of the area, and condemned it as "crummy and misleading".<ref name=Guardian-2014-02-04>{{cite news|first=Caroline |title=Davies |url=http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/feb/04/benefits-street-channel-four-clare-short |title=Benefits Street is excuse for viewers to judge and sneer, says Clare Short |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=4 February 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jefferies |first=Mark |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/benefits-street-channel-4-series-3109953 |title=Benefits Street: Channel 4 series is "totally unrepresentative" of the area, says former Labour MP Clare Short |newspaper=Daily Mirror |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=4 February 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref> Others have also criticised ''Benefits Street'', arguing it does not present a balanced view of the subject. Labour MP [[Anne Begg]], chair of the Commons [[Work and Pensions Select Committee]], said that the programme was a "misrepresentation" of people claiming benefits, arguing that it focused on those claiming unemployment benefits which makes up a small proportion of the overall welfare bill.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/10/benefits-street-misrepresentation-welfare-mp-begg-channel-4 |title=Benefits Street is a 'misrepresentation' of life on welfare, says MP |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> Referring to the first episode that featured a shoplifter, [[Chris Williamson (politician)|Chris Williamson]] (also a Labour MP) said it was "irresponsible" to portray him as a typical benefits claimant.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/TV-s-Benefits-Street-blasted-irresponsible-Derby/story-20468612-detail/story.html |title=Channel 4's Benefits Street blasted as 'irresponsible' by Derby Labour MP |publisher= |newspaper=Derby Telegraph |date=14 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> [[Owen Jones (writer)|Owen Jones]], a columnist for ''[[The Independent]]'' described the series as "medieval stocks updated for a modern format".<ref>{{cite news|first= Jessica |last=Elgot |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/01/10/benefits-street-owen-jone_n_4573811.html |title=Owen Jones Tears Into Channel 4's Ralph Lee Over Benefits Street On Newsnight |publisher=The Huffington Post |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref> In an article for the ''Birmingham Mail'', writer and television personality [[Samantha Brick]], a native of Birmingham, said that the series was an "atrociously unbalanced" view of the city.<ref>{{cite news|first=Christina |last=Savvas |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/samantha-brick-defends-birmingham-after-6679179 |title=Samantha Brick defends Birmingham after Benefits Street - "We're not all on the take and Channel 4 twisted show' |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> Shadow Welfare Minister [[Chris Bryant]] claimed that the residents of [[The Bishop's Avenue]] in [[Hampstead]]{{mdash}}known as Billionaire's Row because of its expensive properties{{mdash}}were as likely to have drink and drugs problems as the residents of James Turner Street.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kashmira |last=Gander |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/billionaires-row-residents-are-as-likely-to-be-drug-addicts-as-people-on-benefits-street-says-labour-mp-chris-bryant-9137080.html |title=As many drug addicts on Billionaire's Row as Benefits Street, says Labour MP Chris Bryant |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=18 February 2014 |accessdate=19 February 2014}}</ref>

[[Fraser Nelson]], editor of ''[[The Spectator]]'', suggested the programme had highlighted a section of society who have been forgotten by the politicians: "These people are people who otherwise don<U+2019>t have a voice. They don<U+2019>t vote, so for many years they have just not mattered".<ref>{{cite news|first=Fraser |last=Nelson |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/10579987/Benefits-Street-the-real-scandal.html |title=Benefits Street: the real scandal |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 January 2014 |accessdate=19 January 2014}}</ref> Nelson's comments were echoed by [[Dominic Sandbrook]] in the ''Daily Mail'', who felt the programme portrayed its participants sympathetically: "The real scandal of Benefits Street, in fact, is what it tells us about a welfare system that abandons thousands of people <U+2013> through no fault of their own <U+2013> to a life without hope or ambition, effectively turning them into an underclass, dependent on the charity of the State."<ref name=Mail-2014-01-18>{{cite news|first=Dominic |last=Sandbrook |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2541568/No-Benefits-Street-does-NOT-demonise-poor-But-shows-immoral-let-welfare-pay-working.html |title=No, Benefits Street does NOT demonise the poor. But it shows how immoral it is to let welfare pay more than working |newspaper=Daily Mail |publisher=Daily Mail and General Trust |date=18 January 2014 |accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref> [[Charlie Brooker]] also felt the programme had been "broadly sympathetic" to those it portrays.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brooker |first=Charlie |url=http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jan/12/benefits-street-poverty-porn-british-fury |title=Benefits Street <U+2013> poverty porn, or just the latest target for pent-up British fury? |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=12 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> In the ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', entrepreneur [[John Bird (entrepreneur)|John Bird]], founder of ''[[The Big Issue]]'' wrote that although ''Benefits Street'' did not fully represent the spectrum of people who claim benefits, it did show what could happen to those forgotten by the system "who get caught in a kind of social suicide".<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Bird |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/big-issue-founder-john-bird-3116153 |title=Big Issue founder John Bird says Benefits Street demonstrates the cycle of poverty and self-destruction which the current welfare system actually encourages |newspaper=Daily Mirror |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref>

====''Benefits Britain: The Debate''====
A live one-hour debate was scheduled to be broadcast by Channel 4 following the final episode of ''Benefits Street''. Channel 4 announced on 16 January that this would be chaired by presenter [[Richard Bacon (broadcaster)|Richard Bacon]] and feature a panel of guests who "represent the views across the political spectrum <U+2013> and crucially those who claim benefits".<ref name=C4-2014-06-16>{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/info/press/news/channel-4-commissions-benefits-street-live-debate |title=Channel 4 commissions Benefits Street live debate |publisher=Channel 4 |date=16 January 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> [[Tinopolis|Mentorn Media]], producers of programmes such as [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' was commissioned to produce the show.<ref>{{cite news|last=White |first=Peter |url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/commissioning/c4-plans-benefits-street-live-debate/5065439.article |title=C4 plans Benefits Street live debate |publisher=Broadcast |date=16 January 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Plunkett |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/16/benefits-street-residents-live-broadcast |title=Benefits Street: residents to get the right of reply in live TV debate |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=16 January 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> Originally scheduled for 10 February, the programme, titled ''Benefits Britain: The Debate'', was subsequently moved back a week to 17 February after rival broadcaster [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] announced plans for a two hour debate about immigration for the same evening. Channel 4 said ''Benefits Britain: The Debate'' would be immediately preceded by a follow up documentary, ''Benefits Street: The Last Word''. The change was announced after many listings magazines had gone to press, a practice generally discouraged in the media industry.<ref name=Guardian-2014-02-06>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Deans |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/06/benefits-street-channel-4-moves-debate-show |title=Benefits Street: Channel 4 moves live debate show back a week |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=6 February 2014}}</ref> 

Panelists for the programme were announced shortly before it aired, and included some ''Benefits Street'' participants, as well as [[Mike Penning]], a minister from the [[Department of Work and Pensions]], Chris Bryant from the opposition, ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]'' columnist [[Allison Pearson]], political editor of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' [[Mehdi Hasan]], and John Bird.<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Plunkett |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/17/benefits-street-white-dee-debate-channel-4 |title=Benefits Street: White Dee and others expected to join live TV debate |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=17 February 2014 |accessdate=17 February 2014}}</ref> Owen Jones, who also participated in the programme, described it as "a rowdy, chaotic show, based on the formula of "who shouts loudest"."<ref>{{cite news|first=Owen |last=Jones |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/owen-jones-my-latest-battle-to-stop-the-demonising-of-people-on-benefits-9136123.html |title=My latest battle to stop the demonising of people on benefits |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=18 February 2014 |accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> This view was echoed by Neil Midgley of ''The Telegraph'', who felt that both follow up programmes "didn't live up to [the] standards" of the series, and that the debate had "sparked a lot of shouting and tumult, but very little new wisdom".<ref>{{cite news|last=Midgley |first=Neil |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10644155/Benefits-Street-The-Last-Word-review.html |title=Benefits Street: The Last Word, review |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 February 2014 |accessdate=17 February 2014}}</ref> ''The Independent''{{'}}s Daisy Wyatt said the programme had "proved as rambling and unfocused as the documentary that sparked the hour-long studio show, with 'neutral' host Richard Bacon veering across topics and adding his own opinions [[Jeremy Kyle]]-style.<ref>{{cite news|first=Daisy |last=Wyatt |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/benefits-street-live-debate-v-the-big-british-immigration-row-9136038.html |title=Benefits Street Live Debate v The Big British Immigration Row |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=18 February 2014 |accessdate=18 February 2014}}</ref> Zoe Wllliams of ''The Guardian'' found the debate "unsatisfactory", feeling the topics discussed were too broad, and that  Bacon was not an effective chair.<ref>{{cite news|first=Zoe |last=Williams |url=http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2014/feb/17/benefits-britain-the-live-debate-live-blog |title=Benefits Britain: the Live Debate <U+2013> as it happened |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=17 February 2014 |accessdate=17 February 2014}}</ref> However, Roz Laws of the ''Birmingham Mail'' described the debate as "articulate" and felt that "interesting points were made, such as the fact that most people on benefits are pensioners yet we didn't see any of them on Benefits Street."<ref>{{cite news|last=Laws |first=Roz |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz-tv/review-benefits-britain---live-6719928 |title=REVIEW: Benefits Britain - The Live Debate |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=17 February 2014 |accessdate=17 February 2014}}</ref> The debate was watched by an average audience of 3.2 million.<ref>{{cite news|first=Elena |last=Cresci |url=http://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/feb/18/benefits-britain-the-live-debate-has-benefits-street-changed-your-view-on-welfare |title=Benefits Britain: the Live Debate - has Benefits Street changed your view on welfare? |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=18 February 2014 |accessdate=18 February 2014}}</ref>

====''The Big Benefits Row: Live''====

[[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] aired ''The Big Benefits Row: Live'', their own unconnected debate about the welfare state on Monday 3 February. Presented by [[Matthew Wright]], the show featured a panel of guests made up of Conservative MP [[Edwina Currie]], reality television star [[Katie Hopkins]], former London Mayor [[Ken Livingstone]], broadcaster [[Terry Christian]], former model [[Annabel Giles]], and two people associated with James Turner Street{{mdash}}charity campaigner Rev. [[Steve Chalke]] and Dierdre Kelly, known in the series as White Dee.<ref>{{cite news|last=Henderson |first=Eugene |last2=Davis |first2=Matthew |url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/457490/Beyond-Benefits-Street-Ghettos-with-70-unemployment-and-no-future |title=Beyond Benefits Street: Ghettos with 70% unemployment and no future |newspaper=Sunday Express |publisher=Northern and Shell |date=2 February 2014 |accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Daisy |last=Wyatt |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/benefits-streets-white-dee-to-join-katie-hopkins-in-live-televised-benefits-debate-9103733.html |title=Benefits Street's White Dee to join Katie Hopkins in live televised benefits debate |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=3 February 2014 |accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref> The programme was watched by 2.1 million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Plunkett |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/04/channel-5-benefits-street-white-dee-katie-hopkins |title=Channel 5 reaps reward of the Benefits Street bandwagon |newspaper=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian Media Group |date=4 February 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref> The ''[[Daily Express]]'' described it as a "heated debate" in which Hopkins was heavily critical of Kelly for claiming welfare, and of Giles's modelling career.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dassanayake |first=Dion |url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/457825/The-Big-Benefits-Row-Katie-Hopkins-and-White-Dee-go-head-to-head-in-welfare-debate |title=The Big Benefits Row: Katie Hopkins and White Dee go head to head in welfare debate |newspaper=Daily Express |publisher=Northern and Shell |date=3 February 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref> ''The Independent''{{'}}s Jess Denham felt that Hopkins's "larger-than-life personality" had dominated proceedings, while "fact-based arguments were lost to the non-stop barrage of immature tempers".<ref>{{cite news|first=Jess |last=Denham |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/the-big-benefits-row-tv-review-live-debate-became-one-big-katie-hopkins-show-9106224.html |title=The Big Benefits Row, TV review: 'Live debate became one big Katie Hopkins Show' |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=4 February 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref> The ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' described it as "a mess of a programme and a joke of a discussion".<ref>{{cite news|last=Leigh |first=Rob |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/big-benefits-row-live-channel-3108957 |title=The Big Benefits Row Live: Channel 5 'Benefits Street' debate with Katie Hopkins and White Dee, as it happened |newspaper=Daily Mirror |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=4 February 2014 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref>

===Public reception===

The first episode of the series attracted several hundred complaints both to Channel 4 and the media regulator [[Ofcom]] from viewers over a variety of issues. According to ''[[The Guardian]]'', complaints were received about alleged criminal activities, foul language and misleading portrayals of welfare claimants.<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-08/> By 8 January 2014, two days after the series debuted, ''Benefits Street'' had attracted 300 complaints to Ofcom and 400 to Channel 4.<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-08/> Three weeks later that figure had collectively increased to 1,700.<ref name=Mail-2014-01-27>{{cite news|first=Alasdair |last=Glennie |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2546445/Benefits-Streets-1-700-complaints-Calls-letters-emails-accuse-glamorising-crime-promoting-drug-use-celebrating-welfare-dependency.html?ITO=1490&ns_mchannel=rss&ns_campaign=1490 |title=Channel 4's Benefits Street receives 1,700 complaints |newspaper=Daily Mail |publisher=Daily Mail and General Trust |date=27 January 2014 |accessdate=27 January 2014}}</ref> Ofcom said that it would assess the viewer feedback before deciding whether to launch an investigation.<ref>{{cite news|first=Paul |last=Suart |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/huge-viewer-backlash-over-benefits-6508865 |title=Huge viewer backlash over Benefits Street |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=15 January 2014 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> After generating a total of 960 complaints to Ofcom and 800 to Channel 4, the broadcasting watchdog announced on 25 February that it would investigate the programme, an inquiry described by ''The Guardian'' as "Ofcom's most high-profile investigation into a TV programme since it cleared Channel 4 of unfair racial stereotyping in ''[[Big Fat Gypsy Weddings]]''".<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Plunkett |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/25/benefits-street-investigated-ofcom-channel-4 |title=Benefits Street to be investigated by Ofcom following viewers' complaints |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=25 February 2014 |accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26336909 |work=BBC News |title=Benefits Street series faces Ofcom investigation |publisher=BBC |date=25 February 2014 |accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref> Additionally, an online petition calling for Channel 4 to cancel the remaining episodes was launched, attracting 3,000 signatures by 8 January.<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-08>{{cite news|first=Hatty |last=Collier |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/08/benefits-street-petition-series-axed-channel-4 |title=Benefits Street backlash continues as petition calls for series to be axed |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=8 January 2014 |accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref> A total of 60,000 people had signed it by the time the series ended on 10 February.<ref>{{cite news|last=Suart |first=Paul |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/benefits-street-set-second-series-3132665 |title=Benefits Street set for second series - but camera crews will not be returning to James Turner Street |newspaper=Daily Mirror |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=10 February 2014}}</ref> The trade union [[Unite the union|Unite]] organised a protest at the offices of Love Productions on the afternoon of 13 January. A group of 30 people attended.<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-14/>

Following the first episode, [[West Midlands Police]] said they had received a number of complaints from members of the public about alleged criminal activities that had been filmed, which they were considering whether to investigate.<ref name=Independent-2014-01-07/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/10558442/Channel-4-documentary-Benefits-Street-faces-police-investigation.html|title=Channel 4 documentary Benefits Street faces police investigation|last=Philipson|first=Alice|date=8 January 2014|work=The Daily Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref> Alleged death threats by Twitter users against the residents were also being probed.<ref name=Channel4-2014-01-07>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/benefits-street-birmingham-channel-4-twitter-row|title='Demonised' or 'humane'? Row breaks out on Benefits Street|date=7 January 2014|publisher=Channel 4|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Jess |last=Denham |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/benefits-street-twitter-reactions-the-angry-the-idiotic-and-the-defensive-9046806.html |title=Benefits Street Twitter reactions: The angry, the idiotic and the defensive |publisher=Independent Print Limited |newspaper=The Independent |date=8 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> Channel 4 said they would not provide investigators with any unbroadcast material from ''Benefits Street'' unless issued with a court order to do so.<ref name=Channel4-2014-01-07/>

The ''Birmingham Mail'' reported on 9 January that the programme had attracted an influx of tourists to the street, who wished to have their picture taken by the James Turner Street road sign.<ref>{{cite news|first=Esh |last=Capelo |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/benefits-street-becomes-tourist-attraction-6483068 |title=Benefits Street becomes tourist attraction with people taking 'selfies' by road sign |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=9 January 2014 |accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref> Police advised visitors to stay away.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lawton |first=Jerry |url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/359962/Police-urge-the-public-to-stay-away-from-James-Turner-Street |title=Police urge the public to stay away from James Turner Street |newspaper=Daily Star |publisher=Northern and Shell |date=11 January 2014 |accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref> Steve Chalke, founder of the Oasis Academy Foundry, a charity that runs a primary school in James Turner Street subsequently said that visitors had disrupted activity at the school and that he was preparing a complaint for Ofcom.<ref>{{cite news|last=Spence |first=Alex |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/medianews/article4000922.ece?CMP=OTH-gnws-standard-2014_02_09 |title=Benefits Street pupils <U+2018>afraid to go to school<U+2019> |format=subscription required |publisher=News International |newspaper=The Times |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Harriet |last=Arkell |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2555721/Benefits-Street-cast-scroungers-drug-addicts-tourist-attraction-controversial-TV-prepares-final-episode.html?ITO=1490&ns_mchannel=rss&ns_campaign=1490 |title=Benefits Street now a tourist attraction as the show prepares for its final episode |newspaper=Daily Mail |publisher=Daily Mail and General Trust |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref> Shortly afterwards, he submitted a letter to the watchdog alleging that children had been subject to public harassment because of the programme, and that Ofcom's rules regarding the welfare of those under the [[age of majority]] had been breached.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dassanayake |first=Dion |url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/460532/Benefits-Street-School-boss-complains-to-TV-watchdog-that-children-receiving-abuse |title=Benefits Street: School boss complains to TV watchdog that children receiving abuse |newspaper=Daily Express |publisher=Northern and Shell |date=18 February 2014 |accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> On 13 February, newspapers, including the ''Daily Mirror'' and ''Daily Star'' reported the theft of the James Turner Street road sign from outside the school.<ref>{{cite news|last=Evans |first=Natalie |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/benefits-street-james-turner-street-3143004 |title=Benefits Street: James Turner Street sign stolen |newspaper=Daily Mirror |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=13 February 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Heffer |first=Greg |url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/365389/Cheeky-thieves-steal-street-sign-from-TV-s-infamous-Benefits-Street-as-souvenir |title=Cheeky thieves steal street sign from TV's infamous Benefits Street as 'souvenir' |newspaper=Daily Star |publisher=Northern and Shell |date=13 February 2014 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>

===Critical reception===

Several James Turner Street residents have claimed they were tricked into appearing in the series by Love Productions, who they say told them it would be about community spirit. One resident told the ''[[Birmingham Mail]]'', "They told me it was about living as a community and how we all got along. But the actual programme doesn't show any of that. If they had said it was about benefits and making the street look bad I would not have taken part. They tricked us."<ref name=Birmingham-Mail-2014-01-06/> Responding to allegations the residents were duped, Nick Mirsky said that Love Productions had spent much time consulting the residents before filming began, and that process continued afterwards: "Key contributors have been offered viewings of the programmes during the editing period and were given the opportunity to comment on them. Both Love and Channel 4 listened to any concerns raised, and in some cases made changes to the programme to accommodate them."<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-10/> Dierdre Kelly, however, subsequently told ITV's ''[[This Morning (TV series)|This Morning]]'' that she believed the programme had provided a one-sided view of her community, and that the residents "went into the show naively".<ref>{{cite news|last=Wightman |first=Catriona |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a552386/benefits-streets-white-dee-we-went-into-the-show-naively.html |title=Benefits Street's White Dee: 'We went into the show naively' |publisher=Digital Spy |date=19 February 2014 |accessdate=19 February 2014}}</ref> Gareth Price of ''The Guardian'' suggested the show's producers "adeptly edited their film in order to provoke a response from its intended audience".<ref>{{cite news|last=Price |first=Garreth |url=http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/feb/22/benefits-street-tv-programme-divided-the-nation |title=Decoding Benefits Street: how Britain was divided by a television show |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=22 February 2014 |accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref>

Sources including ''[[The Independent]]'' and ''[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]'' reported that several commentators had accused Channel 4 of making "poverty porn".<ref name=Independent-2014-01-07/><ref name=Broadcast-2014-01-10/> In response, Ralph Lee refuted those accusations during a debate on the 9 January edition of [[BBC Two]]'s ''[[Newsnight]]'' programme: "It<U+2019>s inaccurate and it<U+2019>s patronising towards the people that take part in these programmes and open up their lives, and it<U+2019>s quite offensive to the people who make them."<ref name=Broadcast-2014-01-10>{{cite news|last=Kanter |first=Jake |url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/broadcasters/c4-rejects-benefits-streets-poverty-porn-tag/5065238.article |title=C4 rejects Benefits Street's <U+2018>poverty porn<U+2019> tag |work=Broadcast |publisher= |date=10 January 2014 |accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> Mirsky claimed the reaction to ''Benefits Street'' demonstrated how it had "touched a nerve" and subsequently proved it was "essential" the series was made.<ref>{{cite news|first=Mayer |last=Missim |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/media/news/a543613/benefits-street-protest-takes-place-at-love-productions-london-offices.html |title=Benefits Street protest takes place at Love Productions London offices |publisher=Digital Spy |date=13 January 2014 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> The boss of Love Productions, Richard McKerrow, also defended the series, saying it was not about "demonising the poor...It<U+2019>s a very honest and true portrayal of life in Britain and people are frightened of it."<ref name=Mirror-2014-01-13>{{cite news|last=McTague |first=Tom |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/benefits-street-iain-duncan-smith-3019449 |title=Benefits Street: Iain Duncan Smith uses poverty porn show to justify savage Tory welfare cuts |newspaper=Daily Mirror |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=13 January 2014 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> Writing as the series concluded, ''The Daily Telegraph''{{'}}s Neil Midgley felt that ''Benefits Street'' had not exploited its participants, and was "definitely the kind of series that Channel 4 should be making: easy to grasp and innovative, and yet a blinding revelation of some ills that are at the heart of modern Britain."<ref name=Telegraph-2014-02-10/>

Emma Johnson, the head teacher of the Oasis school, organised a public meeting on the evening of 15 January to discuss issues raised by the programme.<ref>{{cite news|last=Elkes |first=Neil |url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/benefits-street-school-leads-fightback-3016942 |title=Benefits Street school leads fightback for community 'demonised' by controversial Channel 4 show |newspaper=Daily Mirror |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=13 January 2014 |accessdate=16 January 2014}}</ref> The event was attended by around 100 residents from the area. BBC journalist David Lumb said reporters were not allowed to take pictures, and those present felt the occasion was "an opportunity to preach a political agenda".<ref name=BBC-2014-01-16/> The meeting was told that an employed couple who were filmed for the series were dropped from the final version. Love Productions said this was because the show was about people on benefits, and one of the unnamed pair was a benefits officer.<ref name=BBC-2014-01-16>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-birmingham-25750475 |work=BBC News |title=Benefits Street: Working couple 'cut' from Channel 4 show |publisher=BBC |date=16 January 2014 |accessdate=16 January 2014}}</ref>

After the third episode was televised on 20 January, the ''Daily Mail'' reported that community leaders and residents had accused Channel 4 of exploiting children, claiming it had led to the children featured in the documentary becoming targets for bullying. In response, a Channel 4 spokeswoman said that consent from parents and guardians, and the children themselves was obtained before filming began "in accordance with the relevant sections of the Ofcom broadcasting code. Any children without consent have been blurred in programmes."<ref name=Mail-2014-01-21>{{cite news|first=Rob |last=Cooper |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2543320/Benefits-Street-child-exploitation-row-Was-Channel-4-right-use-young-children.html |title=Benefits Street child exploitation row |newspaper=Daily Mail |publisher=Daily Mail and General Trust |date=21 January 2014 |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Edgar |first=James |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/10588979/Channel-4-accused-of-exploiting-children-for-Benefits-Street.html |title=Channel 4 accused of exploiting children for Benefits Street |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=22 January 2014 |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref>

The ''Birmingham Mail'' reported on 10 February that figures released to the newspaper by [[Birmingham City Council]]'s fraud investigation service indicated instances of benefit fraud in the city were lower than had been suggested by the documentary, with   851 prosecutions in the five years preceding 2014, an average of 0.5% of total benefit claimants. Furthermore, of the 152,000 housing benefit claimants in Birmingham, 178 were prosecuted for fraudulent claims in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|first=Nick |last=McCarthy |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/benefits-street-truth-benefit-fraud-6689371 |title=Benefits Street: The truth about benefit fraud in Birmingham |publisher=Trinity Mirror |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=10 February 2014 |accessdate=12 February 2014}}</ref>

===Viewership===
Overnight figures indicated the show's first episode attracted 4.3 million viewers and a 17.7% share of viewing, more than any Channel 4 show in the whole of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/benefits-street-channel-4-documentary-2994242|title=Benefits Street: Channel 4 documentary stars hit out at portrayal of life in James Turner Street, Birmingham|last=Suart|first=Paul|date=6 January 2013|work=Daily Mirror|publisher=Trinity Mirror|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref> The second instalment, aired on 13 January, saw an increase of almost a million viewers to 5.1 million, a 20.8% share of the audience and beating ITV's ''[[The Bletchley Circle]]'' and an edition of ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' on BBC One and its own former show ''[[Celebrity Big Brother (UK)|Celebrity Big Brother]]'' (now on Channel 5) which aired in the same time slot.<ref name=Guardian-2014-01-14>{{cite news|first=John |last=Plunkett |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/14/benefits-street-viewers-channel-4 |title=Benefits Street adds nearly 1 million viewers for second episode |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 January 2014 |accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref> The third episode drew 5.2 million viewers giving it a 21.2% share of the audience, making it the most popular programme in the 9:00 pm time slot for the second week in a row, and giving Channel 4 their highest ratings since their coverage of the [[2012 Summer Paralympics closing ceremony|closing ceremony]] of the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in September 2012.<ref name=Mail-2014-01-21a>{{cite news|first=Chris |last=Pleasance |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2543261/Benefits-Streets-parade-scroungers-drug-addicts-Channel-4-highest-ratings-2012.html |title=Benefits Street gives Channel 4 its highest ratings since 2012 |newspaper=Daily Mail |publisher=Daily Mail and General Trust |date=21 January 2014 |accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Fred |last=McConnell |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/21/benefits-street-5m-audience-channel-4 |title=Benefits Street draws more than 5m for a second week |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=21 January 2014 |accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref> The fourth episode attracted less viewers, however, with an average of 4.1 million, and was behind the first part of [[Jeremy Paxman]]'s [[World War I]] documentary series, ''[[Britain's Great War]]'', which aired on BBC One and had an average viewership of 4.23 million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Eames|first=Tom|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a547060/benefits-street-dips-to-41-million-on-channel-4.html|title=Benefits Street dips to 4.1 million on Channel 4|publisher=Digital Spy|date=28 January 2014|accessdate=28 January 2014}}</ref> The final episode drew 4.5 million viewers, an 18.6% audience share, but was beaten by ITV's ''[[DCI Banks]]'' which was watched by an average 6 million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jason |last=Deans |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/11/benefits-street-tv-ratings-channel-4-love-production |title=Benefits Street ending pulls in 4.5 million |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>

